        <mi>S</mi>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding="application/x-tex">{\displaystyle S}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src="https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/render/svg/4611d85173cd3b508e67077d4a1252c9c05abca2" class="mwe-math-fallback-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden="true" style="vertical-align: -0.338ex; width:1.499ex; height:2.176ex;" alt="{\displaystyle S}"></span> have a notion of equivalence (formalized as an <a href="/wiki/Equivalence_relation" title="Equivalence relation">equivalence relation</a>), then one may naturally split the set <span class="mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class="mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style="display: none;"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"  alttext="{\displaystyle S}">
